h as an Umbrella Trust</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (UT)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> or a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Multi-Academy T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rust</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (MAT)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There are now 356 independent chains</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of two or more schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">comprising</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 1648</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> academies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of which 975 are primary</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> phase</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We are supporting primary schools to come together in these partnerships through the Primary Chains Grant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">–</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> £50,000</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is available </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for groups of three</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> or more schools applying to form a MAT where the majority of the schools are primary.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> appetite for a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ca</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">demy status </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is apparent across the whole country. There are academies in all LAs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> except the City of London and the Scilly Isles (which have one maintained primary each)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. In </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">four</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> LAs (Darlington, North East Lincolnshire, Bexley and Rutland) all secondary sc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hools h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ave converted to academy status. Another </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">78 have more secondary academies than LA-maintained secondary schools.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In Darlington and North East Lincolnshire </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">over half of the state funded primary schools are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> also academies.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There are 26 LAs where 20% or</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> more of state</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">funded primary schools are open as academies.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">With the expansion of academies and free schools greater choice is being given to parents and de</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mand for places is high. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Free schools that were open in September 2012 self-reported they had rece</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ived an average of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">three</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> applicants per place for September 2013. The King’s Leadership Academy in Warrington opened in 2012 in an area with surplus school places but the free school is oversubscribed: it received 266 expressions of interest for 120 Year 7</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> places in September 2014, and of those 140 made the school their first preference</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in their application.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Academy growth is built on a track record of improving standards. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The first sponsored academies were very successful in tackling failure.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Analysis </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">published by the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">epartment last year shows that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> between 2005/06 and 2009/10</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the proportion of pupils achieving five good GCSEs including English and maths </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in sponsored academies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">improved by just over 21%.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Nearly double the rate of improvement seen </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nationally over the same period</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In 2013</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in secondary sponsored academies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the percentage of pupils achieving fiv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e or more good GCSEs rose by 1.8%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. As academies mature, they continue to improve. Sponsored academies that have been open for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">three years ha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ve improved by 12</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">since opening </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(to 48.2%), compared to a 5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">% </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">increase in maintained schools over the same period. In primary sponsored academies result</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s improved by three </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">this year</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Harris Academy Greenwich </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is an excellent example of the transformative </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">impact a sponsored academy can have. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hrough tackling truancy and careful targeting of resources, such as the pupil premium, the academy is reporting 85% of pupils achieving five</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> good GCSEs in 2013. This is up from 43% in 2011.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is not just sponsored academies that are successful. Converter academies are maintaining their already high standards: in 2013, 81% of pupils achieved level 4 or above in reading, writing and mathematics in primary converter academies, compared to 76% i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n LA-maintained mainstream </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">schools. 25% of their pupils </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">were </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">above</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the expected standard at age 11 compared to 21% of pupils across all state-funded schools</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In secondary converter academies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">67.9</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">% of pupils achieved five good GCSEs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">including English and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> mathematics</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> compared to 58.8% of pupils in LA-maintained</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> schools</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Converter</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s do better </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">than LA maintained schools </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">against the new</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tougher Ofsted framework. Converter academies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in both phases</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are more likely to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">retain their ‘Outstanding’ rating from Of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, with 33% of primaries, and 35% of secondary academies maintaining their rating, compared to 25% and 33% respectively, in maintained schools. Converter academies are also</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> more lik</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ely to improve from ‘Good’ to ‘Outstanding’ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">than LA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">maintained schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with 27% of primary academies, and 16% of secondary academies, compared to just 12% of maintained primaries and 10% of secondaries improving to an ‘outstanding’ rating</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> This high performance is being mirrored in the first set of free school inspection resu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lts. Four</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of the original 24 free schools which opened in 2011 have already been rated ‘Outstanding’, whilst 14 have achieved ‘Good’</span><a name="_Ref375048615"></a><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.5pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">All academies are responding well to a new</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">qualification</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> regime. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In converters</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 43.3% of pupils are now entered for the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">EBacc compared to 33.8% in LA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">maintained schools. In sponsored academies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the number of pupils entered for the qualification has doubled in the last year to 21.7% in 2013</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Academies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">driv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> up standards </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for the majority</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">– </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">importantly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">– </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sponsored academies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">do better for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the most deprived. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Results for pupils eligible for free school meals (FSM) have improved faster than in comparable LA-maintained schools. In 2012, the proportion of FSM pupils gaining five or more good GCSEs (including Eng</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lish an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d mathematics) increased by 2.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">% in spons</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ored academies, compared to 0.9</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">% in similar LA schools.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For pupils with Special </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Educational Needs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, the proportion gaining five or more good GCSEs including Eng</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lish and maths increased by 3.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">% between 2011 and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 2012, compared to an increase of 0.3% in similar LA schools</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Such improvement is vital for economic growth.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Sutton Trust found that if we boost the educational outcomes of the less educated families to match the UK average it could mean a 4% increas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e in GDP by 2050, or £60 billion as a share of today’s economy</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Academies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> help</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to achieve such a boost</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A study of the performance of early sponsored academies by Machin and Vernoit (2011)</span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> at the LSE found that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">improved performance in the academie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s led to significant improvements in neighbouring schools. The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">author’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> state: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“We do not believe that this is a coincidence: it suggests that it is possible for performance improvements in an academy to generate significant beneficial external effects on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">their neighbouring schools.”</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Academies succeed because they have the space to innovate.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Academies are at the cutting edge of the education system, using their freedoms to innovate and improve standards.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Many school leaders feel a general sense of liber</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ation with academy status”</span><a name="_ftnref19"></a><a href="#_ftn19">[19]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and head</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">teachers in academies feel that they have permission to innovate. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">many</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> examples of academies up and down the country using their freedoms to improve standards. Trinity Academy Halifax has used their budget freedom to offer a responsive and performance related pay package for their teaching staff. This has greatly improved st</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">aff retention and results. In 2013, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">72% of pupils achieve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> five</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> good GCSEs (including English and maths), a massive improvement from 48% in 2010 when Trinity became an academy. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.5pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Free School Norwich has changed the way the school year is organised</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to oper</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ate a six</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">term year, with an extended school service to help working families, and a shorter summer holiday. The extended school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">operates both during term time and throughout the school holidays from 8.15 am until 5.45 pm. The school is closed for only one</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> week a year – at Christmas. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> noticed a big impact on boys where the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">shorter </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">four</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">week </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">summer break has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">meant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that standards are retained and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">they can hit the ground running in the autumn term</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">King Solomon Academy has used the fre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">edom to change their curriculum and extend the school day </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to deliver </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">seven</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> additional hours of English a week and 30 minutes of extra maths daily. King Solomon has since bee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n rated ‘Outstanding’ by Ofsted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">At Harris Academy Bermondsey have pioneered a ‘Me</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ntors from Business’ programme, which matches men and women from top flight City companies with one-to-one with girls from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">their</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> school as they prepare for their exams. The weekly meetings are held before or after the Academy day. The school also now runs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a ‘Mentors</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> from Universities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> programme which pairs year nine students with undergraduates from LSE and London South Bank University. Innovations like these have led the school to report a record 67% of pupils achieved five good GCSEs (and equivalent) incl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uding English and maths in 2013.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Academies are driving improvement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">across the schools system through collaboration</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> and partnership working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Collaboration is a defining feature of the academies programme. As academies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have been </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">freed from local authority control they </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are leading a developing system of school-to-school support: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">shar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">expertise, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">provid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> challenge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and improving</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> standards</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> across the education sector</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.5pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Academies sit at the heart of t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">each</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing school a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lliances.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 185 of the 357 teaching schools are academies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (52 primaries, 124 secondary and 9 special</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">academies)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Teaching schools provide </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">outstanding initial training, robust teacher development and strong leadership – all based around a sound understanding of “what </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">works”. They establish a network of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">alliances</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that drive significant improvement in the quality of professional practice, improving the attainment of every child.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">100 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">academies are part of these teaching school alliances. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Academies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">also play</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a key role in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">school-centred initial teacher training centres (SCITTs). </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">55 academies are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">now SCITT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span s